solutions.content:
**Explanation -**
       The key idea is **NOT** to do the operations one by one. **Lets consider cases-**

1.  **Odd Numbers -** Instead of randomly adding or subtracting **1** from the number, try to think **1-step** ahead, when you add or subtract 1 from any odd number, you get an even number, **BUT** after dividing that number by 2 - **You get EVEN result for a case & ODD for the other**. Consider - 

**Eg: 21**   

         (21+1) = 22              and                   (21-1) = 20
         22/2 = 11 (Odd)			                     20/2 = 10 (Even) 
**Thus here we need to SUBTRACT 1 from the number**

2. **Even Numbers -** Here if we keep dividing by 2 on each step, we will get **TLE** so instead **divide the number by - HIGHEST POWER OF 2** that divides that number and add the power to the number of steps.


**Here is the Java Code to implement the above logic -**
```
class Solution {
    public int integerReplacement(int n) {
//         Base Case
        if(n==1) return 0;
        int c = 0;
//         Actual loop
        while(n!=1){
//             Condition for odd
            if(n%2!=0){
                int sub = n-1;
                if((sub/2)%2==0 || (sub/2)==1) n-=1;
                else n+=1;
                c++;
            }
			// Condition for Even Case
            else if(n%2==0){
                // Check the highest power of 2 to divide n
                for(int i=31; i>=1; i--){
                    if(n%(1<<i)==0){
                        n = n/(1<<i);
                        c+=i;
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return c;
    }
}
```

