solutions.content:
The idea is to decrease the `n` as quick as possible. 
If `n` is even, we divide it by 2 and we get `n / 2`.
If `n` is odd, we use two step: +1 or -1 then divide it by 2, and we can get `n / 2` or `n / 2 + 1`. We recurse on them and use the smaller one.
We never have to increase `n`, so no overflow issue.

3-liner (4 ms):
```
public int integerReplacement(int n) {
	if (n == 1) return 0;
	if (n % 2 == 0) return integerReplacement(n / 2) + 1;
	return Math.min(integerReplacement(n / 2),  integerReplacement(n / 2 + 1)) + 2;
}
```

With memoization (0 ms):
```
public int integerReplacement(int n) {
	Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
	map.put(1, 0);
	return memoization(n, map);
}

private int memoization(int n, Map<Integer, Integer> map) {
	if (map.containsKey(n)) return map.get(n);
	int res = 0;
	if (n % 2 == 0) res = memoization(n / 2, map) + 1;
	else res = Math.min(memoization(n / 2, map), memoization(n / 2 + 1, map)) + 2;
	map.put(n, res);
	return res;
}
```

