# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We have three different cases to account for:
- n == 1 (Base case)
- n % 2 == 0 (n is even)
- n % 2 != 0 (n is odd)

## Key points:
- n is stated to be a positive integer (n > 0) => We <b>don't</b> need to validate input (i.e. What happens if we pass in a negative? What if we don't pass in an integer?)
- We want the <b>minimum</b> of steps
- With recursion we may want to introduce <b>memoization</b> in order to reduce the amount of repeated work 

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Create a HashMap to store memoized results (Key = n, Value = number of 'steps' at n to reach 1)
- If n == 1 (Base case)
    - We return 0 (no steps are needed to reach '1')
- Check if n is in our map, if so return map.get(n)
- Else if n % 2 == 0 (n is even)
    - We divide n by 2 and pass the result into our recursive function
    - We add 1 to our count to account for the 'step' we just took
    - Place result in HashMap
- Else (n is odd)
    - We add 1 to n and we subtract 1 from n and pass each of these results into our recursive function
    - We return the minimum of the above result
    - We add 1 to our count to account for the 'step' we just took
    - Place result in HashMap
- Return map.get(n)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N)$$. Each number, starting at 2 up to and including N, is visited, computed and then stored for O(1) access later on.

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$. The size of the stack in memory is proportional to N. Also, the memoization hash table is used, which occupies O(N)space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
  Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
  public int integerReplacement(int n){
    if (n == Integer.MAX_VALUE) return 32; //n = 2^31-1;
    if(n == 1) return 0;
    if(map.containsKey(n)) {
      return map.get(n);
    } else if(n % 2 == 0) {
      map.put(n, integerReplacement(n/2) + 1);
    } else {
      map.put(n, Math.min(integerReplacement(n+1), integerReplacement(n-1)) + 1);
    }
    return map.get(n);
  }
}
```

