# Greedy Solution
```
class Solution:
    def integerReplacement(self, n: int) -> int:
        count = 0
        while n > 1:
            count += 1
            if n & 1 == 0:
                n //=2
            else:
                if n == 3:
                    n -= 1
                elif n & 3 == 3:
                    n += 1
                else:
                    n -= 1
        return count

```

Idea is pretty simple 
If number is even : ....1010 ( Any binary representation ends in 0 ) , its better to remove last bit and make it 1 step closer to 1 , hence, n // 2.

What not very clear is what if its odd : ...01 or ...11 ( Ending in 01 / 11 . These are the only two possible representations for odd numbers ) 
If we have ...01 , adding 1 will make it ...10 ( no gain ) , subtracting will make it 00 ( gained by removing 1 bit ) , Hence for this case subtraction is better
If we have ...11, adding 1 will make it  ..100( we removed ***atleast*** 2 1's and will gain just 1 ( atleast 1 gain ) , subtracting will make it ...10 ( just gain of 1) . So in this case Adding will always perform same/better than subtracting . 
And n == 3 is a special case ( Seperate Handling for that )


*********

# DP Solution
```
class Solution:
    def integerReplacement(self, n: int) -> int:
        return self.helper(n,0)
    def helper(self,num,steps_to_1):
        if num == 1:
            return steps_to_1

        if num % 2 == 0:
            return self.helper(num//2,steps_to_1+1)
        else:
            return min( self.helper(num+1, steps_to_1+1), self.helper(num-1,steps_to_1+1)  )
```

First code shows Recursive Solution and Second one shows modifications done to First Solution to make it DP ( Memoization ) Solution 
```
class Solution:
    def integerReplacement(self, n: int) -> int:
        self.cache = dict() # down to up steps , up to down steps is tracked using steps_to_1
        return self.helper(n,0)
    def helper(self,num,steps_to_1):

        if num in self.cache:
            return self.cache[num] + steps_to_1
        if num == 1:
            return steps_to_1

        if num % 2 == 0:
            rv = self.helper(num//2,steps_to_1+1)    
        else:
            rv = min( self.helper(num+1, steps_to_1+1), self.helper(num-1,steps_to_1+1)  )

        self.cache[num] = rv-steps_to_1
        return rv
```

