# Idea

When `n` is even there is only one choice - divide by 2.

Otherwise we have two choices: add 1 or sub 1. Divide & rule gives best result if we choose between +/- such that the outcome is divisible by 4. 

*There is one exception to this rule. When n == 3. For these cases we use precomuted results stored in an array.*

*Also to pass the test case where n == Integer.MAX_VALUE, I am making use of an auxilary method.*

Enjoy!

```
class Solution {
    int[] sol = new int[]{0,0,1,2,2};

    public int integerReplacement(int n) {
        if(n==Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            return 2+integerReplacements(n/2 + 1);
        }
        return integerReplacements(n);
    }

    public int integerReplacements(int n) {
        if(n < 5) return sol[n];
        if((n&1) == 1) {
            if((n + 1) % 4 == 0) {
                return 2+integerReplacements((n+1)/2);
            } else {
                return 2+integerReplacements((n-1)/2);
            }
        }
        return 1+integerReplacements(n/2);
    }
}
```

