solutions.content:
# Intuition
The general idea is very simple - listing all points avaliable in some certain order and store them in a list, whenever we call pick(), we generate a random index and return that point.

# Approach
There's two things we need to discuss:
**1. what's that "certain order"** 
**2. how to store all points**

In each rectangle, we could iterate all points from left to right, bottom to top. And we follow the relative order among all rectangles(given by input).
![90a1f529ee79dd399219b8f03816f50.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b7b83aca-3249-4287-a19d-e5f0ebe97fd6_1677327674.4030004.jpeg)

Listing all points and save them in a container is rather stupid due to the high time and space complexity. 
Why not store an index range for each rectangle. For instance, in the picture above, we know the green rectangle owns points indexed from 1 to 16, the blue one owns 17 to 28, so we could generate a table like this:
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6d745003-cea3-41ee-9e3c-e97ff30da9df_1677328183.0795298.png)
Actually, we don't need to save the left bound of each range -- when  trying to find out which rectangle a point is in, we could just find the first range whose right bound >= point index. For example, point at index 25 lies in rectangle 1, because 28 >= 25; point 58 stays within rectangle 2 because 58 >= 58.

As a result, the final table we save looks like this:
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/bd3cd2e7-8b2e-488a-a560-80fd5dfd3647_1677329511.9538338.png)


This structure could be represented by a tree-map (map<int,int>) in C++. DO NOT use a hash map - we need a structure maintaining the order of point indexes.

Thanks to C++ map's "upper_bound" function, we can easily find the first key(left column of the table above) larger than some input within O(logn) time. 

One special case is that when the input happens to be some key in the map, the map would return the next key. For instance, if input = 28, the map would return the 2-indexed rectangle. So we should check it first.

After we locate the rectangle index, get the point is just piece of cake.


# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(log(n))

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
private:
    const vector<vector<int>>& allrects;
    int total_points;
    map<int, int> point_rect;
public:
    Solution(vector<vector<int>>& rects): allrects(rects) {
        total_points = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<rects.size();++i) {
            total_points += getPointCount(rects[i]);
            point_rect[total_points] = i;
        }
    }

    int getPointCount(const vector<int>& rect) {
        int width = rect[2] - rect[0] + 1;
        int height = rect[3] - rect[1] + 1;
        return width * height;
    }

    vector<int> pick() {
        int original = rand() % total_points + 1;
        map<int,int>::iterator it;
        auto temp = point_rect.find(original);
        if(temp != point_rect.end()) {
            it = temp;
        } else {
            it = point_rect.upper_bound(original);
        }
        int rect_index = it->second;
        const vector<int> rect = allrects[rect_index];
        int index_inside_rect = it->first - original;
        int width = rect[2] - rect[0] + 1;
        int y_offset = -index_inside_rect / width;
        int x_offset = -index_inside_rect % width;
        int y = rect[3] + y_offset;
        int x = rect[2] + x_offset;
        return {x,y}; 
    }
};

