92 prcntle speed and 91 prcntle memory with no usage of - rand() % size - which internally has a little bias.

# Intuition

Consider rectangles with area r1, r2, r3, r4, ..., rn.

1.  Probability of picking a point from rectangle 1 is ```1/n . 1/r1```
i.e. choose the rectangle with probability 1/n followed by probability of chosing a point from the rectangle.

2.  So picking a point from each rectangle have probabilities ```1/(n.r1), 1/(n.r2), ..., 1/(n.rn)```.

3. Clearly, this is not a uniform distribution unless all rectangles have equal area.

4. **So the idea here is to adjust the probability of picking the rectangle such that effect of the varying areas are nullified.**

5. This can be done by changing the probability of picking rectangle  r1 to ```r1/(r1+r2+...+rn) ```

6. i.e. we need a non-uniform/weighted probability distribution to select the random rectangle.

7.  Now, the probability for picking a point from rectangle 1 has changed to ```r1/(r1+r2+...+rn) . 1/r1 = 1/(r1+r2+...+rn).```
8. Similarly for rectangle r2 ```r2/(r1+r2+..+rn) . 1/r2 = 1/(r1+r2+..+rn)```.

9. Making the required distribution uniform with probability ```1/(r1+r2+..rn)```.
10. Note this only holds if none of the rectangles overlap or even share the side with each other.

# Notes
1. There is already another linked problem explaining how to achieve a weighted/non-uniform probability distribution using cumulative sums in O(log(n)).

2. This is the discrete version of the inverse transform sampling in statistics - for more reference to theory.

```
class Solution {
public:
    Solution(vector<vector<int>>& rects_input)
        : rects(std::move(rects_input)),
          mt(std::random_device{}())
    {
        auto cum_wt = 0;
        for(auto const& rect : rects)
        {
            cum_rect_wts.emplace_back(cum_wt += (static_cast<std::uint64_t>((rect[2] - rect[0] + 1)) * (rect[3] - rect[1] + 1)));
        }
    }

    vector<int> pick() noexcept
    {
        auto rand_rect_wt = std::uniform_int_distribution{1ul, cum_rect_wts.back()}(mt);
        auto rect_index = std::distance(cum_rect_wts.begin(),
                                        std::lower_bound(cum_rect_wts.begin(), cum_rect_wts.end(), rand_rect_wt));
        auto& rect = rects[rect_index];
        return {std::uniform_int_distribution{rect[0], rect[2]}(mt),
                std::uniform_int_distribution{rect[1], rect[3]}(mt)};
    }
private:
    std::vector<std::uint64_t> cum_rect_wts;
    std::vector<std::vector<int>> rects;
    std::mt19937 mt;
};
```

