solutions.content:
So, the basic idea is:
1. Print points rectangle by rectangle.
2. Choose 1st rectangle and print all its points. Lets say rectangle leftmost and rightmost co-ordinates are: (x1, y1) and (x2, y2).
	a) print co-ordinates of bottom row of the rectangle: Start from (x1, y1) and increment x1 till point (x2, y1).
	b) Once the bottom row co-ordinates are all printed, then take next row from the bottom and print that row completely (x1, y1+1) to (x2, y1+1).
	c) Once all points for that rectangle is printed, choose next rectangle.
	d) After all rectangle points are printed, choose the first rectangle again.

```
class Solution {

    public int[][] rects;
    public int x=Integer.MIN_VALUE, y;
    public int rect=0;
    public int rectangleCount;

    public Solution(int[][] rects) {
        this.rects = rects;
        rectangleCount = rects.length;
    }

    public int[] pick() {

        // for first run, choose first rectangle co-ordinates.
        if(x==Integer.MIN_VALUE) {
            x = rects[rect][0];
            y = rects[rect][1];
        }

        // print all points for that row.
        else if(x+1 <= rects[rect][2] && y <= rects[rect][3]) {
            x = x + 1;
        }

        // If all the row points are printed, choose row just above to previous bottom row.
        else if (x+1 > rects[rect][2] && y+1 <= rects[rect][3]) {
            y = y + 1;
            x = rects[rect][0];
        }

        // If all points of that rectangle is done, choose next rectangle.
        else if (x+1 > rects[rect][2] && y+1 > rects[rect][3]) {
            rect = (rect+1) % rectangleCount;
            x = rects[rect][0];
            y = rects[rect][1];
        }
        return new int[] {x, y};
    }
}
```

